 memoirs, and public papers, Carol K. Winkler uncovers how presidents have capitalized on public perceptions of the terrorist threat, misrepresented actual terrorist events, and used the term "terrorism" to influence electoral outcomes both at home and abroad. Perhaps more importantly, she explains their motivations for doing so, and critically discusses the moral and political implications of the present range of narratives used to present terrorism to the public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aIdeologyxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aIdeologyzUnited States. 0aPolitical oratoryxUnited States. 0aPolitical oratoryzUnited States. 0aPresidentsxLanguagexUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxLanguage. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aTerrorismxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aTerrorismxGovernment policyzUnited States. 4aHistory : American History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791482537423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791482537/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles